                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d51">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">810.20 Defense/163⅜ Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Brazil</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rio de Janeiro</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-06-14T00:00:00-03:00"
                            >June 14, 1940—midnight</date>.<lb/>[Received June 15—5:30
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>281. For Under Secretary. My 279, June 14, 7 p.m.<note n="62" xml:id="d51fn1">Not
                        printed.</note> In this armament matter the Brazilian military authorities
                    since July speak very highly of General Marshall and in no way blame him for the
                    failure of arms to come from the United States. They understand our legislative
                    difficulties.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
